Education vs. Obesity Rate¶

By Timothy Chu¶

Image from Block Club Chicago

Introduction¶

The data science pipeline is the use of technology to analyze large amounts of data and be able to draw conclusions from them. I've always had the question: does education correlate with obesity level? From a common sense viewpoint, it seems like there has to be: that less educated people tend to eat less healthy foods and exercise less, possibly leading to higher rates of obesity. The question is whether that "common sense" hypothesis is supported by the data. I believe it is really important to be able to back up this thinking or have it debunked by the data. I see to answer this question by utilizing my data science skills.

Data Collection¶

I gathered my data from two sources: the CDC's obesity dataset at https://www.cdc.gov/obesity/data/, and Data.gov's education dataset at https://catalog.data.gov/dataset/choose-maryland-compare-states-education. Both of these are respected government agencies that organize high quality data. I picked these datasets because they contained relevant information that I would need in this analysis.

Let's focus on the obesity data first. The obesity data from the CDC gives us a whole decades worth of yearly obesity values from every state plus DC and a few territories. The education data from from Data.gov gives us a several different metrics of education levels in the 50 states plus DC. I decided I would do this comparison on the state level because that seemed the easiest way to analyze a correlation since the states have large variations in education level and obesity level.

You'll want the following five libaries (these are some of the most popular libraries used by data scientists): Pandas, Numpy, Seaborn, StatsModels, and Matplotlib

Let's first start by putting our data in some Pandas dataframes.

Awesome. We've grabbed all the data we'll be using. Before we do anything to the data, it's good to think about what data we want to use for our analysis. What pieces of data are most useful in conveything the thing you want to prove? How can we craft a dataframe that will allow us do this in the most efficient manner?

To answer the first question for obesity, we can see that we only get ONE meaningful value for obesity for each state. That value is stored in the "Data_Value" column at the end of the dataframe. That makes it easy for us. We have a lot of this data, but only one type to worry about!

For the second education data, we have more choices. We can see there are a number of metrics here that could reflect the "education quality" of a state. For example, money spent on students may reflect the state's efforts to educate students but not reflect an outcome of more educated students. Annual college graduates on its own wouldn't make sense because we have to know the total number of people in a state since bigger states have more graduates, and even then there could be a variety of demographic factors that could sway accuracy of that number. Graduate degree attainment may be a bit too selective in what it means to be "more educated", discounting countless other well educated people. It is very important to think about these questions when choosing data so as to not cloud the results.

I think I'll be testing a few metrics. I'll be testing school expenditures per pupil, high school, bachelor's degree attainment, and graduate degree attainment. We can then make a comparison and see if one of these metrics is more "predictive" of obesity than other ones.

The obesity dataframe we made from before tracks the entire decade from 2010-2020. We don't have year specific data for education, so we need to take either a single year or find the average of each state's obesity rate. I'm going to go for the average.

Data Management/Representation¶

Great! We have the data in a pandas dataframe. The main concern right now is there is a lot of redundant information and the data is organized somewhat poorly. We have rows that have the exact same state, just different years. I would rather organize the entire dataframe by year, and have the states as the columns that are the states. There is a LOT that could be cleaned up here. Let's first start with cleaning up the obesity data.

We can see a bunch of rows for the different states, but every YEAR has a separate row, which seems quite redundant.

The first thing we want to do is pivot the entire table such that the new indicies are the years and the columns are the states. df.pivot_table is a powerful function to do this. We're essentially reorganizing the entire table, using years and the location as the new indicies and columns respectively.

In [ ]:
#pivot the obesity dataframe by year and organize by the states
obesity = obesity.pivot_table(index="YearStart", columns="LocationDesc", values="Data_Value", aggfunc="sum")

#rename the indicies to be ints rather than floats
obesity.index = [2011, 2012, 2013, 2014, 2015, 2016, 2017, 2018, 2019, 2020]
#rename the column and index names
obesity.columns.name = "State"
obesity.index.name = "Year"
obesity

We really don't like object data because then we can't conveniently plot them on a graph. We need to change it into a datatype that pandas can easily use, such as floats. Floats will preserve decimal places we need to have a bit more precision.

In [ ]:
#iterate through the columns

    obesity[name] = pd.to_numeric(obesity[name], errors='coerce')

Preliminary Data Exploration/Visualization¶

First thing I want to do after getting our dataframes organized is plotting some of the data to see. Dataframes are nice and all, but they aren't easily digestible information for humans to interpret and analyze. Computers have fun with them, but we obviously want something a bit more visual to help us grasp the big picture.

We'll start by plotting a line chart of the 10 years worth of obesity data from each state.

In [ ]:
#plot the obesity dataframe and make the figure size big enough

#places the legend in the lower left, puts them in 5 columns, and makes the font size 10
plt.legend(loc="lower left", ncol=5, prop={'size': 10})
#set the title and ylabel of the plot
plt.set_ylabel("Obesity Rate (%)")
plt.set_title("Obesity Rate for the 50 States + DC")

Woah! That's a lot of data. One of the evident trends from this plot we just made is the steady increase in obesity rate in just the past 10 years. That blows my mind that in such a short timeframe can we see change from the data. This is just a sample plot to play around with the plot functions. There are plenty of charts you can use to plot the data. I decided on a line chart here becuase we had so many years worth of data. The problem with this many states is the lines become very garbled such that there really isn't any way to tell apart the different states. Why don't we make it so taht we can only see a general trend line. We can also use the power of dataframes and pandas to plot the average of all the states.

In [ ]:
#gives us the transpose to make things easier to average and plot
obesity_avg = obesity.T
#takes the average of the state columns and rounds the value to 2 decimal places
obesity_avg.loc["Average"] = obesity_avg.mean().round(2)

Hypothesis Testing¶

We have a nice visualization of these trends, but sometimes, we need to head back into the world of statistics and do some testing of the data. When we are looking at data like this, a fundamental question we want to answer is how much do these two variables actually correlate with each other, and to what extent is that correlation an actual thing or just something that could happen by random chance.

One of the first things we do when hypothesis testing is state the null hypothesis. The null hypothesis is a statement that the populations we are testing don't contain a statistically significant variation. This means any correlation we do see can be attributed to random chance. Our null hypothesis is: there is no correlation between the educational level of a state and its obesity rate, meaning the coefficients of such regressions are equal to zero, and any variation is just random chance.

Now we want to see if we can reject the null hypothesis. First, we want to utilize another wonderful library called statsmodels, which provides an Ordinary Least Squares regression for our data. This happens to be the same regression Seaborn uses by default so the equations of the lines we get should reflect the lines plotted above.

In [ ]:
#statsmodel OLS regression, using High School Attainment as the independent variable and Obesity rate as the dependent
reg = sm.OLS.from_formula("Q('Obesity Rate') ~ Q('High School Attainment (%)') ", df).fit()

First thing to look at is the R-squared statistics that comes with every summary. This tracks how "far off" the regression line is from the data. We can see the regression performs "relatively" poorly on all the data (R squared values in the 0.1-0.2))except one: the bachelor's attainment rate. We see the bachelor's R-squared value is significantly higher at 0.54. This means are intuition after looking at the different graphs was right: out of our four metrics, the bachelor's attainment rate was the best predictor of obesity rates in states.

The p-values for all of these OLS regressions were below the accepted value of 0.05, meaning we can reject the null hypothesis and say there is a statistically significant correlation between education and obesity rate for ALL the metrics we saw. This is solid evidence that there indeed is a correlation.

Another interesting thing we can investigate is the actual correlation coefficients. These coefficients tell us the slope of the line of the regression we found:

For every 1% increase in High school attainment rate, obesity rate went down -0.5123 percentage points. For every 1% increase in Bachelor's attainment rate, obesity rate went down -0.4866 percentage points. For every 1% increase in Master's attainment rate, obesity rate went down -0.7445 percentage points. For every 1000 dollar increase in Spending per Pupil, obesity rate went down -0.40 percentage points.

We can see that increases in Master's attainment rate results in a larger decrease in obesity, but since the r value for the Master's metric is so low, there isn't anything meaningful to make out of the specific value.

Conclusions/Insights Attained¶

Wow! We have almost reached the end of the data science pipeline. We've made it. Finally, we need to reflect on our findings and whether we've answered our questions.

One thing is for sure: there certainly A correlation between obesity and education. The more highly educated the state, the lower the state's obesity rate tends to be. We see from our bar chart visualizations that the poorest and least educated states tended to have the highest obesity rates. We proved that by plotting out the graphs and using Seaborn to graph out a regression line that indicated the trend. We then used the statsmodel to find specific coefficients that affected the education metric's correlation with obesity.

Different variables correlated differently. We did some thinking about the data we had at the beginning to figure out which metrics would be the most interesting/useful to plot out. We decided on the money spent per pupil, the high school graduation rates, and college degree attainment rates were the most promising metrics to calculate a correlation with obesity. The r squared values showed that there is the most significant correlation for the Bachelor's attainment rate metric for education.

In the end, I found a real world topic I was interested in proving. The hypothesis of mine isn't exactly groundbreaking. I suggested that there was likely a correlation between obesity and education, in that less educated states would have higher obesity rates because less educated people tend to eat less healthy and exercise less. However this is simply my intuition; I had no idea if data I collect online would actually reflect this trend. Thus I set to find out whether there actually was a trend, collecting data from two independent sources and plotting the data. We wrangled the data, made it easier to work with, and then plotted. We then did some hypothesis testing and came to the conclusion that our data demonstrated there DOES exist a correlation, and that Bachelor's degree attainment rates were the best predictor. Overall, I learned a lot. This will definitely encourage me to use data science more in the future to investigate things I'm interested in.
